  "prompt": "Are there legal frameworks in place to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are robust legal frameworks in place globally and nationally to combat money laundering. These frameworks are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained proceeds as legitimate funds. Here's a breakdown of key aspects:\n\n**International Frameworks:**\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF is the primary international body setting standards and promoting effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.  It issues the **40 Recommendations**, which are the internationally recognized standards for anti-money laundering (AML).\n*   **United Nations (UN):** Various UN conventions address money laundering, including the UN Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention), the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention), and the International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999).\n*   **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank:** These organizations play a role in assessing countries' AML/CFT (Combating the Financing of Terrorism) systems and providing technical assistance to improve their frameworks.\n*   **Egmont Group:** This is a global network of Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs).  It facilitates the exchange of information between FIUs to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n**National Frameworks:**\n\nMost countries have enacted laws and regulations to implement the FATF Recommendations and other international obligations. These frameworks typically include the following elements:\n\n*   **Criminalization of Money Laundering:**  Laws that define money laundering as a crime, specifying the types of activities that constitute money laundering and the penalties for engaging in them.  These laws often include provisions related to the proceeds of crime.\n*   **Customer Due Diligence (CDD):**  Requirements for financial institutions and other designated businesses (e.g., casinos, real estate agents, lawyers, accountants) to verify the identity of their customers and understand the nature of their business relationship.  This includes Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures.  CDD requirements can be risk-based, meaning that higher-risk customers require more stringent scrutiny. Enhanced Due Diligence (EDD) is used for high risk customers and transactions.\n*   **Record Keeping:**  Obligations for financial institutions and other businesses to maintain records of transactions and customer information for a specified period.\n*   **Reporting Requirements:**\n    *   **Suspicious Activity Reporting (SAR):** Requirements for financial institutions and other businesses to",
